      'result': """CVE-2025-55182 is a critical pre-authentication Remote Code Execution (RCE) vulnerability affecting React Server Components (RSC) and frameworks that implement them, such as Next.js, React Router with RSC APIs, Expo, Redwood SDK, Waku, and various Vite and Parcel plugins. Disclosed on December 3, 2025, by the React team, this vulnerability has been assigned a maximum CVSS score of 10.0, indicating its severe nature due to the lack of authentication or user interaction required for exploitation and a direct path to remote code execution. It is also referred to as "React2Shell" and incorporates CVE-2025-66478, which was merged into it.

The root cause of CVE-2025-55182 lies in an unsafe deserialization flaw within React's "Flight" protocol, specifically in how the server processes incoming payloads. Affected versions of RSC packages "trust the received data too much" and attempt to deserialize any data sent by the user without proper validation. This allows an attacker to craft a malicious payload, disguised as a legitimate "Chunk" object, which React then attempts to resolve as a promise during its internal request parsing logic. By controlling the `then` method of this fake Chunk, attackers can manipulate internal request states and ultimately gain control over server-side execution.

Exploitation of this vulnerability is possible under the default configurations of several popular frameworks, making it widely exploitable. Attackers can execute arbitrary code on vulnerable servers by sending a single malicious HTTP POST request containing the crafted input. Exploitation activity related to CVE-2025-55182 has been detected in the wild as early as December 5, 2025, primarily targeting internet-facing Next.js applications and Kubernetes containers. Observed post-exploitation activities include cloud credential harvesting and cryptocurrency mining.

The high impact and ease of exploitation make immediate patching essential for organizations utilizing React Server Components in production environments. Recommendations include upgrading to patched versions of affected frameworks and implementing layered security measures such as Defender monitoring and Web Application Firewall (WAF) protections. Microsoft Defender for Endpoint has expanded its detection framework to identify and alert on CVE-2025-55182 activity, integrating with automatic attack disruption to help contain and stop attacks."""
    }
  )
), Part(
